I had the great fortune of celebrating Tibetan New Year in Nepal, learning about Tibetan Buddhism, and hanging out with monks for over a week now

One phrase that is repeated constantly is “peace to all sentient beings” 

I have deep gratitude for these monks who are chanting for YEARS to bless us with peace and protection. 

I was asked to spend time with these monks so I taught them dodgeball, secret handshakes, had a pizza party and even trips to the zoo. 

I fell in love with these monks after hearing about their stories and sharing so many experiences with them. This post is to share with you my joy from these small moments, a reminder of how little we need and how small things can make a difference in many people’s lives. 

For example, taking 70+ monks to the zoo and lunch costs around ~$200 a small amount that created a lifelong experience for so many
Happiness ☺️

In 2005, Steve Jobs gave a commencement speech at Stanford - one thing he mentions is his dropping out of college and taking a random calligraphy class, not knowing it would have any actual application to his life.

If he didn’t drop out and take that random class, personal computers might not have fantastic typography as they currently do.

This was my 30th birthday, and I was invited to speak at an Afghan rally due to the injustice that was happening there.

I was the only non-Afghan person who was invited to speak. Although I didn’t fully understand the situation, I knew they needed love, and I wanted non-Afghans to support them. Ultimately, we all desire acceptance and love.

So that’s what I conveyed to them. I expressed that I cared about them and wanted to demonstrate that, despite not knowing them personally, I felt their pain and stood with them.

After my speech, a few elderly women approached me, hugged me, and cried on my shoulders. I didn’t know how to react initially, but I stayed there, trying to be strong for them.

Until that moment, I didn’t realize the impact of my voice. Despite speaking at many rallies before, it was only then that I truly understood the power my voice held.

#qi (pronounced “chee”) is  well known concept in the East. Imagine you have an energy inside your body, like a hidden power. This energy is called qi. It’s like the fuel that keeps everything in your body working properly. Just like electricity flows through wires to make things work, qi flows through channels in your body called meridians, keeping you healthy and strong.

When your qi is flowing smoothly, you feel good and full of energy. But  things like stress, illness, or negative emotions can block the flow of qi, causing you to feel tired or unwell. That’s why it’s important to take care of yourself, so your qi can flow freely and keep you balanced and healthy.

You can think of qi like a river. When the river flows smoothly, everything around it thrives. But if there are obstacles in the river, the water can become stagnant and things may not grow well #taoism #easternphilosophy

Samantabadri is a name derived from two components: “Samanta” and “Badri.” Samanta generally conveys the idea of universality or all-encompassing, while “Badri” refers to the sacred Badrinath mountain in the Himalayas. Samantabadri could symbolize a universal or all-pervading sacred presence, which is often associated with compassion and a deep sense of interconnectedness with all beings.

On the other hand, Samantbadra which is a well-known figure in Buddhism. Samantabhadra is considered the bodhisattva representing wisdom and skillful means (compassionate actions). He embodies the qualities of wisdom, compassion, and boundless virtue, making him a symbol of the ideal practitioner on the path to enlightenment.

Combining these meanings, their sacred union could be seen as the harmonious merging of compassion and wisdom, reflecting the understanding and realization of the interconnected nature of all things and the compassionate actions that arise from such wisdom.

Why this is so important:

1️⃣ Self-Love and Independence: Before seeking love from someone else, it’s crucial to love and be comfortable with yourself. When you’re happy on your own, you bring a whole and confident self into any relationship. This makes you less dependent on others for your happiness and more resilient when facing challenges.

2️⃣ Setting Healthy Standards: When you’re content with yourself, you’re less likely to settle for less than you deserve in a relationship. You’ll have clear standards and boundaries, which are vital for a healthy, balanced partnership.

3️⃣ Attracting the Right Person: Being happy by yourself is like a magnet for the right person. When you exude self-assuredness and positivity, you naturally attract people who appreciate and complement your life, rather than those who might bring negativity or drama.

4️⃣ Building a Strong Foundation: A solid relationship is built upon two individuals who are already strong and whole on their own. This creates a foundation of trust, respect, and support that can withstand the ups and downs of life.

Remember, it’s not about avoiding dating until you reach some unattainable level of perfection. It’s about working on self-improvement and self-acceptance, so you bring your best self to the dating world. 💪

The right person will come into your life when the time is right. Until then, enjoy your own company, pursue your passions, and grow as an individual. ❤️✨ #DatingAdvice #SelfLove #Relationships #LoveYourself
